<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Calamagrostis canadensis </i>is a sod-forming, perennial, cool-season grass that grows to 1.2 m. It has winged seeds that are lightweight, easily wind-borne and that are viable in the soil for up to 5 years. The roots are shallow, the rhizomes are extensive, and resulting sod is long-lasting. This plant prefers moist sites, but can survive in a wide range of moisture regimes. It is tolerant of extremely acidic soils, and moderately tolerant of saline soils. <i>C. canadensis </i>is the most common and widespread <i>Calamagrostis </i>in North America (Tesky 1992a). <br/>
<br/>
The alliance occurs across the western United States and Canada in montane wet areas (NatureServe 2007a). In California, the alliance tends to occur as small stands in a matrix with other wet and moist meadow alliances, or it occurs along stream margins in meadows or forest openings. It grows on both peat and mineral soils, but most often on peat, and is adapted to a wide range of soil textures (Tesky 1992a). <i>C. stricta </i>ssp. <i>inexpansa </i>has been sometimes confused with <i>C. canadensis </i>in vegetation surveys in the Sierra Nevada (Potter 2005). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
