    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Calamagrostis canadensis</i> includes montane and subalpine elevations in the Klamath Mountains (M261A) and the Southern Cascades (M261D).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ee, Eh, Ej-q). Descriptions from Sequoia National Park (Benedict 1983, Halpern 1986) and Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) characterize the alliance in California. In addition, Cooper and Wolf (2006) recognized the alliance in transitional fens of Sequoia National Forest. Potter (2005) found <i>C. canadensis</i> as an important understory species in the <i>Pinus contorta</i> ssp. <i>murrayana/Vaccinium uliginosum-Rhododendron columbianum</i> association.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Calamagrostis canadensis </i>is an important forage for livestock and mule deer in the Sierra Nevada (Potter 2005). Intensive grazing reduces both biomass and seed production. <i>C. canadensis </i>often produces a thick layer of litter that insulates the soil surface, causing soil temperatures to decrease. Cold soils may reduce the growth of conifer seedlings in reed grassdominated sites (Tesky 1992a). </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
